00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:20.000
This video demonstrates the operation of the PT6.

00:00:20.000 --> 00:00:25.000
The bed size of the PT6 is 48” deep x 96” wide.

00:00:26.000 --> 00:00:28.000
This permits the fabrication of a wide range of products.

00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:32.000
42 pairs of form arms define the inner 
 surface of the component to be formed.

00:00:33.000 --> 00:00:41.000
The position of the form arms is controlled by a series of 
 DC stepper motors which are linked to the computer control system.

00:00:42.000 --> 00:00:50.000
This system allows the manufacturer to rapidly set up and manufacture a 
 component without the use of forms or templates of any kind.

00:00:51.000 --> 00:01:03.000
Once entered, all the pertinent manufacturing information to make a part is stored on the computer 
 hard drive, and can be recalled at any time to reproduce an identical component.

00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:20.000
A heavy stainless steel band, suspended over the bed by 2 carriages, is tensioned by hydraulic brakes and 
 is used to form the component to the form arms and provide the necessary laminating pressure.

00:01:23.000 --> 00:01:29.000
The component to be formed is placed on the stock positioners.

00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:40.000
The machine has a maximum width capacity of 11 inches and is provided with 2 
 sets of adjustable stock positioners, permitting 2 parts to be run per machine cycle.

00:01:41.000 --> 00:01:44.000
Pressing a button on a console begins the machine cycle.

00:01:44.000 --> 00:01:51.000
The overhead bridge moves forward and the tensioned stainless steel 
 band forms the component to the form arms.

00:01:54.000 --> 00:02:07.000
Remove the stainless steel or wood fillers used on 
 the inside of the part being formed.

00:01:57.000 --> 00:02:07.000
Once the part is dried, the machine automatically cycles 
 to prepare for the removal of the part.

00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:38.000
The filler distributes the contact force of the form arms 
 uniformly along the inside surface of the part.

00:02:44.000 --> 00:02:46.000
Let’s take a closer look at the machine details.  

00:02:48.000 --> 00:02:56.000
Each of the 42 pairs of form arms are mounted on a common 
 driven shaft which is in turn coupled with a geared stepper motor.

00:02:57.000 --> 00:03:07.000
Once the stepper motors have positioned the form arms in their correct location, they are individually locked 
 firmly in place by a hydraulic clamp built into the base of each arm.  

00:03:09.000 --> 00:03:13.000
This provides a stable and accurate surface to define the 
 inner perimeter of the part to be formed.

00:03:16.000 --> 00:03:20.000
The heavy stainless steel band is suspended over the bed by 2 carriages.

00:03:21.000 --> 00:03:30.000
The stainless steel band is tensioned by adjustable hydraulic brakes and used to form 
 the component to the form arms and provide the necessary laminating pressure.

00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:38.000
The stainless steel tension band is also the 
 negative conductor for the radio frequency generator.

00:03:42.000 --> 00:03:49.000
The bridge is mounted on machine slides and 
 is driven by a large gear motor.

